Full CTX-tooling update entry point for a scaffolded project: syncs `install-tools.sh`, runs it to rebuild/copy `ctx-*` binaries, then mirrors a fixed list of pure-tooling files (clippy/rustfmt/deny configs, check scripts, runtime prompt files, `.claude/settings.json`) from an upstream CTX repo, and finally splices just the tool-contracts block into this project's `CLAUDE.md`.

`CTX_REPO` is `$1` or `$CTX_REPO` env var, defaulting to `../CTX`, matching `install-tools.sh`'s own default — path validity is not checked here, it's delegated to `install-tools.sh` failing fast. Every mirrored file is overwritten unconditionally every run; no diffing or skip-if-modified logic.

The mirror lists are hardcoded and deliberately partial: `TOP_LEVEL_FILES`, `CHECK_SCRIPTS`, and `PROMPTS` name specific files, not directories — adding a new check script or prompt upstream requires updating this array too, or it silently won't sync. Excluded on purpose: `auditor.md`, `prompts/README.md`, `prompts/manual/` (CTX-repo-internal, not runtime input), and most of `template/` like `Cargo.toml` and `CLAUDE.md`'s prose (project-owned).

The `CLAUDE.md` sync is a splice, not a copy: it extracts the region between `<!-- BEGIN GENERATED tool-contracts... -->` and `<!-- END GENERATED tool-contracts -->` markers from the CTX repo's `template/CLAUDE.md` (already regenerated there by `gen_tool_contracts.sh`) and replaces only that region in the local `CLAUDE.md` via `awk`, preserving surrounding project-specific prose. Marker strings must match `scripts/gen_tool_contracts.sh` exactly — if that file's markers change, this script breaks silently (grep checks will just start failing loudly, per the `FAIL:` guards on missing markers/files in both source and local `CLAUDE.md`).

`install-tools.sh` is synced to disk *before* being invoked, so the run always executes the latest upstream version, not whatever local copy the project was scaffolded with. This script syncs *itself* last, after all other steps, because Bash reads a running script in chunks and overwriting mid-execution isn't safe for multi-step scripts.